## 3. Character Stats

Character Stats: Light and Shadow

In this ACT-based life RPG, the player’s character is defined not only by “positive” psychological skills, but also by their “shadow” counterparts.

Positive stats represent stable skills the player has developed.

They never decrease; they either grow or stay the same.

Once you’ve learned defusion or acceptance, that capacity is there, even if you don’t use it all the time.

Shadow stats represent how much the character is currently caught in old, unhelpful patterns.

They increase with away moves (actions driven by avoidance, fusion, autopilot, etc.).

They decrease with toward moves (values-based actions) and specific in-game practices.

This way the player can see both growth and regression clearly:
skills can be high and the shadows can temporarily flare up when life gets hard.

Core Stat Pairs

Each core ACT process is represented as a pair: a light stat (skill) and a shadow stat (its counterpart).

3.1. Psychological Flexibility / Psychological Inflexibility

Psychological Flexibility
The main “global” stat of the character. It reflects the ability to stay present, open up to inner experience, and act in line with personal values.
High Psychological Flexibility means the character can adapt to difficulties, feel what they feel, and still choose effective, values-based actions.

Psychological Inflexibility
The shadow counterpart: how much the character is currently trapped in rigid, unhelpful patterns — dominated by avoidance, fusion, and automatic reactions.
A higher Psychological Inflexibility score makes other shadow stats more impactful and increases the chance of getting stuck or derailed by internal experiences.

3.2. Acceptance / Experiential Avoidance

Acceptance / Willingness
Measures the character’s readiness to experience discomfort in the service of what matters.
High Acceptance means the character can carry fear, pain, or shame along for the journey without shutting down or fighting their inner world.

Experiential Avoidance
The shadow stat: how strongly the character is trying to get rid of or escape from unwanted thoughts and feelings.
Experiential Avoidance grows when the player consistently chooses away moves to dodge discomfort (numbing, distraction, procrastination instead of facing what matters).
It shrinks when the player does small, values-based actions while allowing discomfort to be there.

3.3 Cognitive Defusion / Cognitive Fusion

Cognitive Defusion
The skill of seeing thoughts as thoughts – words, images, and stories – rather than literal truths or commands.
High Defusion means the character can notice thoughts like “I’m a failure” without automatically believing or obeying them.

Cognitive Fusion
The shadow: how entangled the character is with their thoughts right now.
When Cognitive Fusion is high, the character treats thoughts as facts, gets hooked by mental stories, and behaves as if the mind is always right.
Fusion grows when the character repeatedly cancels quests or actions because of thoughts like “I can’t”, “It’s pointless”, or “I’ll be judged”.
It decreases when the player uses in-game defusion techniques and still acts according to values.

3.4. Mindfulness / Autopilot

Mindfulness (Focus)
Represents the ability to connect with the present moment and fully engage with what is happening here and now.
High Mindfulness improves the effectiveness of all actions: quests completed with high focus grant more experience and better outcomes.

Autopilot (Mindlessness)
The shadow stat: how much the character is running on automatic, disconnected from the present.
High Autopilot means reacting instead of choosing, scrolling instead of participating, zoning out instead of engaging.
Autopilot rises when the player repeatedly goes through days and quests mechanically, avoiding awareness.
It drops when the player practices short in-game mindfulness exercises or completes quests consciously and intentionally.

3.5. Values Alignment / Values Disconnection

Values Alignment
Shows how closely the character’s actions are aligned with their chosen values.
It can be tracked globally and per value (e.g., Health, Relationships, Creativity).
High Values Alignment provides bonuses to motivation, recovery after setbacks, and unlocks deeper story events connected to meaning and fulfillment.

Values Disconnection (Values Drift)
The shadow side: how far the character has drifted away from what truly matters to them.
Values Disconnection increases when the player frequently chooses short-term comfort or fear-driven decisions over what they’ve declared as important.
It decreases when the player takes even small, concrete steps in each values area, reinforcing the link between intention and action.

3.6. Committed Action / Avoidant Inaction

Committed Action
Measures the character’s ability to take consistent, values-based steps, even in the presence of fear, doubt, or discomfort.
High Committed Action means more quests get completed, fewer projects die halfway, and the character can translate insight into behavior.

Avoidant Inaction (Stuckness)
The shadow: how much the character is currently stuck in non-doing, delay, or impulsive detours that serve avoidance rather than values.
Avoidant Inaction grows when quests aligned with values are repeatedly postponed, abandoned, or replaced with easy, numbing activities.
It shrinks when the player starts and finishes small, realistic actions that move the character toward their values, even if those steps are tiny.

This dual-stat system lets the player see both sides of their psychological journey:

Positive stats show what skills they have built over time.

Shadow stats show how much old patterns are active right now.

Together they paint a clear picture of both long-term growth and current struggles, which fits perfectly with ACT’s focus on psychological flexibility in the real, messy flow of life.

